03:17.438 --> 03:20.855
The ocean makes the sunset
look so special,

03:20.939 --> 03:23.939
but you make it spectacular.

03:24.021 --> 03:26.689
The sun is getting jealous.

03:26.772 --> 03:31.647
♪♪♪

03:33.897 --> 03:35.313
You're welcome.

03:35.397 --> 03:39.188
♪♪♪

03:39.271 --> 03:41.105
Dolphins!
Dolphins.

03:41.188 --> 03:42.605
Do you see the dolphin?

03:42.689 --> 03:43.647
There's a dolphin.

03:43.730 --> 03:48.855
♪♪♪

03:50.897 --> 03:52.605
Hey.

03:54.980 --> 03:59.271
We need to talk
before he gets here.

03:59.355 --> 04:01.897
Okay.

04:01.980 --> 04:04.563
You first.

04:04.647 --> 04:07.230
I've been thinking
about this a lot,

04:07.313 --> 04:10.980
and I feel that...

04:11.063 --> 04:13.522
if it would make you happier,

04:13.605 --> 04:16.772
for M-Maddy
to take piano again,

04:16.855 --> 04:18.855
then she should take piano,
and I'll just deal with it.

04:18.939 --> 04:20.105
Oh.

04:20.188 --> 04:21.355
She seemed happier.

04:21.438 --> 04:23.480
I don't think that's true.

04:23.563 --> 04:26.897
Plus, she's getting
so good at clarinet.

04:26.980 --> 04:28.271
- [Maddy] I am?
- Yes, honey.

04:28.355 --> 04:29.855
I just think she may have

04:29.939 --> 04:31.021
liked piano better,

04:31.105 --> 04:34.188
and if her heart
is set on piano,

04:34.271 --> 04:36.438
then you just--you can't change
someone's heart.

04:36.522 --> 04:37.397
I think

04:37.480 --> 04:39.563
piano was just a phase.

04:39.647 --> 04:40.814
You do?

04:40.897 --> 04:41.605
[Maddy]
It was?

04:41.689 --> 04:42.730
Yes, sweetheart.

04:42.814 --> 04:44.188
I think she was confused.

04:44.271 --> 04:47.021
She was born
a clarinet player.

04:47.105 --> 04:49.271
Piano's just
this weird choice she made.

04:49.355 --> 04:52.772
She was never really
committed to piano.

04:52.855 --> 04:54.271
She--she probably wishes

04:54.355 --> 04:56.397
she never took piano
in the first place.

04:56.480 --> 04:57.939
[Maddy]
Was I not good at piano?

04:58.021 --> 04:58.897
It was awful.

04:58.980 --> 04:59.897
Dee Dee, from now on,

04:59.980 --> 05:01.271
we are strictly

05:01.355 --> 05:02.689
a clarinet family.

05:02.772 --> 05:05.063
I am committed

05:05.146 --> 05:07.313
to making this
a clarinet family.

05:10.188 --> 05:13.689
[Maddy] You guys need to be
more supportive of my dreams.

05:13.772 --> 05:15.397
[doorbell rings]

05:15.480 --> 05:18.355
♪ easygoing music ♪

05:18.438 --> 05:20.313
Konnichiwa.

05:20.397 --> 05:21.563
[laughs]

05:21.647 --> 05:23.522
Konnichiwa.

05:23.605 --> 05:24.897
Pikurusu-san desu.

05:24.980 --> 05:25.980
[Scott] Maddy?

05:26.063 --> 05:27.980
This is Mr. Pickles-san.

05:28.063 --> 05:30.730
He's gonna follow Uncle Jeff
around for a few weeks

05:30.814 --> 05:32.939
and then bring back
what he learned to Japan.

05:33.021 --> 05:33.980
And occasionally babysit.

05:34.063 --> 05:38.188
speaking Japanese

05:38.271 --> 05:41.230
Oh, I'm--I'm sorry
Jeff couldn't host you.

05:41.313 --> 05:42.855
His living situation
isn't optimal

05:42.939 --> 05:44.063
to board guests right now.

05:44.146 --> 05:47.480
My... English I...
Mm...

05:47.563 --> 05:50.271
Not amazing.
[laughs]

05:52.897 --> 05:54.647
♪ gentle music ♪

05:54.730 --> 05:55.814
Sado-Shimi.

05:55.897 --> 06:00.897
speaking Japanese

06:00.980 --> 06:03.855
♪♪♪

06:03.939 --> 06:05.814
Sado-Shimi?

06:05.897 --> 06:06.939
Sou.
Sado-shimi.

06:07.021 --> 06:07.939
[Maddy] Thank you.

06:08.021 --> 06:08.980
[Pickles-san] Thank you.

06:09.063 --> 06:10.480
Arigatou.

06:10.563 --> 06:15.397
♪♪♪

06:17.522 --> 06:19.271
[Jeff]
I have a message, all right,

06:19.355 --> 06:21.730
but I don't know
if they're gonna like it.

06:21.814 --> 06:26.730
♪♪♪

06:37.563 --> 06:39.647
We're ready to record
whenever you're ready.

06:39.730 --> 06:42.522
Okay.

06:49.647 --> 06:52.063
All of history

06:52.146 --> 06:55.063
travels on the human voice.

06:55.146 --> 06:58.730
Amplified, it can shear
a man in half,

06:58.814 --> 07:01.730
sentence 2 million Polish Jews
to Dachau,

07:01.814 --> 07:02.980
or spread the Book of Matthew

07:03.063 --> 07:05.939
from Mount Zion
to a Roman river.

07:06.021 --> 07:08.230
Thousands of malleable minds

07:08.313 --> 07:10.146
will rip this doll
off the shelf,

07:10.230 --> 07:11.230
and I don't know
if they'll see it

07:11.313 --> 07:14.271
as a god or gremlin.

07:14.355 --> 07:17.647
But...

07:17.730 --> 07:19.647
I won't drop nightshade
into children's ears.

07:21.980 --> 07:24.438
Um, so, I don't think
we're allowed

07:24.522 --> 07:26.271
to stray
from the approved script.

07:26.355 --> 07:28.271
I'd like to,

07:28.355 --> 07:30.105
if that's all right.

07:30.188 --> 07:32.980
[woman] Of course.
What do you want to say?

07:36.522 --> 07:38.063
[Jeff] Allahu akbar!

07:38.146 --> 07:40.480
Allahu akbar?

07:40.563 --> 07:42.897
No, I don't like
those words.

07:42.980 --> 07:45.271
They scare the dirt
off of me.

07:45.355 --> 07:47.146
Well, maybe
they'll be less scary

07:47.230 --> 07:49.105
if we explain what they mean.

07:49.188 --> 07:50.563
[Jeff] Allahu akbar
is an expression

07:50.647 --> 07:52.438
that means
a lot of different things.

07:52.522 --> 07:54.438
[Jeff] Mainly, it's used
as a greeting,

07:54.522 --> 07:57.730
like we say "Hello,"
"good-bye."

07:57.814 --> 08:00.563
[as Uke-Larry]
Or... "aloha"?

08:00.647 --> 08:03.063
That's right,
Uke-Larry.

08:03.146 --> 08:04.814
So if we went to Hawaii,

08:04.897 --> 08:08.021
we could say,
"Aloha-u akbar."

08:08.105 --> 08:10.647
Um... Sure.

08:10.730 --> 08:12.689
Allahu akbar.

08:12.772 --> 08:15.647
Forced to leave
their homes at gunpoint

08:15.730 --> 08:18.230
and march on foot
with whatever they could carry.

08:18.313 --> 08:20.313
It led to the deaths
of over 20,000

08:20.397 --> 08:22.939
Indigenous Americans.

08:23.021 --> 08:24.855
"Indigenous"?

08:24.939 --> 08:26.522
Indigenous.

08:26.605 --> 08:28.730
[Jeff] That means
they were here first.

08:28.814 --> 08:31.522
The Cherokees called this
the Trail of Tears.

08:31.605 --> 08:33.480
Oops.

08:33.563 --> 08:35.230
That's right, Oops.

08:35.313 --> 08:37.772
Even governments
make mistakes.

08:37.855 --> 08:40.563
♪ whimsical music ♪

08:40.647 --> 08:42.730
Disconnect
the teleprompters.

08:42.814 --> 08:44.730
I did.
That's just him talking.

08:44.814 --> 08:47.522
[Rabbi Epstein] Grace and I
wrote him a powerful scene

08:47.605 --> 08:49.188
in which Snagglehorse
goes apple-picking,

08:49.271 --> 08:52.063
and he wrote,
"Despair is an eagle."

08:52.146 --> 08:54.188
[Rabbi Epstein]
What does that mean?

08:54.271 --> 08:56.105
♪♪♪

08:56.188 --> 08:59.271
Without a diverse group
of meaningful relationships,

08:59.355 --> 09:01.146
we can't see
certain populations

09:01.230 --> 09:02.730
as actual people,

09:02.814 --> 09:05.647
and we subconsciously
tune them out.

09:05.730 --> 09:07.480
[Jeff] And your depression
is something

09:07.563 --> 09:09.605
you should never
be afraid to talk about

09:09.689 --> 09:11.063
with the people you love,

09:11.146 --> 09:13.063
because if they really
love you...

09:13.146 --> 09:15.230
They'd tell you
that Ronald McDonald

09:15.313 --> 09:18.063
wants to walk our black youth
into a food desert

09:18.146 --> 09:20.397
and leave them there
without their pants on,

09:20.480 --> 09:22.522
because he wants
to charge you for water

09:22.605 --> 09:24.355
and he wants
to charge you to pee.

09:24.438 --> 09:28.689
Don't expect compliments
from an insecure person.

09:28.772 --> 09:30.313
Too many people think
this country's

09:30.397 --> 09:32.230
a stone-cold gray corpse,

09:32.313 --> 09:33.647
but it's not.

09:33.730 --> 09:36.063
It's a living,
breathing organism.

09:36.146 --> 09:38.814
♪♪♪

09:38.897 --> 09:40.689
And we've got
to keep kicking it

09:40.772 --> 09:42.980
to make sure it's alive.

09:43.063 --> 09:44.689
Yee-haw!

09:44.772 --> 09:46.980
For every 90 minutes
of footage we shoot,

09:47.063 --> 09:48.855
only 12 are borderline usable,

09:48.939 --> 09:50.689
and that's before we cut out

09:50.772 --> 09:52.647
the veiled Marxism
and songs about genocide.

09:52.730 --> 09:54.772
[Jeff yelling]

09:54.855 --> 09:55.939
Whoo--hoo!

09:56.021 --> 09:57.397
The show
was right there

09:57.480 --> 10:00.397
beneath the surface
the whole time

10:00.480 --> 10:03.605
[both gasping]

10:03.689 --> 10:05.271
I thought it was an end,

10:05.355 --> 10:07.105
but it was just a rust

10:07.188 --> 10:09.105
oxidized over the beginning.

10:09.188 --> 10:11.230
♪♪♪

10:13.313 --> 10:16.105
Sorry.
I forgot my eyeballs.

10:16.188 --> 10:19.480
speaking Japanese

10:23.313 --> 10:26.188
Thank you.

10:26.271 --> 10:28.105
Allahu akbar.

10:30.230 --> 10:31.730
Good night.

10:37.438 --> 10:39.855
He can do whatever he wants.

10:39.939 --> 10:41.897
Say whatever he wants.

10:41.980 --> 10:44.188
Maybe I want
to look in a lens

10:44.271 --> 10:45.730
and scream a little.

10:45.814 --> 10:47.230
speaking Japanese

10:47.313 --> 10:49.730
Not that they'd let me
near a camera.

10:49.814 --> 10:52.563
Sometimes, I--
I'm Soap Scum's

10:52.647 --> 10:54.814
limp right hand,
and even then,

10:54.897 --> 10:57.647
it's obscured
by a shower curtain

10:57.730 --> 11:00.689
that... I created
in my dorm room.

11:05.063 --> 11:06.563
[American accent]
The true artist...

11:06.647 --> 11:08.313
is both victim and warrior.

11:08.397 --> 11:10.105
You speak English?

11:10.188 --> 11:11.730
I'm not speaking English.

11:11.814 --> 11:14.689
♪ wondrous music ♪

11:14.772 --> 11:17.271
♪♪♪

11:17.355 --> 11:22.480
speaking Japanese

11:25.188 --> 11:26.355
♪♪♪

11:26.438 --> 11:27.647
Oh.

11:27.730 --> 11:32.897
♪♪♪

11:34.855 --> 11:36.689
What makes
your puppets special

11:36.772 --> 11:39.438
is the life you put
inside of them,

11:39.522 --> 11:41.063
not the people
hiding behind them.

11:41.146 --> 11:46.313
♪♪♪

11:51.438 --> 11:53.980
What's your real name,
Pickles-san?

11:54.063 --> 11:56.939
Mm, who I was doesn't matter.

11:57.021 --> 11:58.772
I'm Pickles-san now,

11:58.855 --> 12:01.146
always and forever.

12:01.230 --> 12:03.980
Maybe we both like to hide.

12:04.063 --> 12:08.021
I hide from myself
all the time.

12:08.105 --> 12:11.355
I think that's why
I married Scott.

12:11.438 --> 12:13.397
He's...

12:13.480 --> 12:15.146
I didn't want to know myself,

12:15.230 --> 12:18.647
so I chose a man
who could never know me.

12:18.730 --> 12:23.271
He's the one who wanted kids.

12:23.355 --> 12:24.980
I only exist

12:25.063 --> 12:26.313
for other people:

12:26.397 --> 12:29.021
Maddy and Scott and Jeff

12:29.105 --> 12:30.730
and my dad and...

12:30.814 --> 12:33.563
♪♪♪

12:33.647 --> 12:36.188
It's easy to exist for them,

12:36.271 --> 12:40.689
because I don't know how
to exist for myself.

12:40.772 --> 12:45.271
I don't know how to want.

12:45.355 --> 12:47.605
I'd rather bleed
in front of a doll

12:47.689 --> 12:51.188
than live
in front of my family.

12:51.271 --> 12:54.021
♪♪♪

12:54.105 --> 12:56.897
That's how I grew up.

12:56.980 --> 13:01.271
We are a family
who loves from afar.

13:01.355 --> 13:03.897
But loving others
from afar means

13:03.980 --> 13:06.814
what they give you in return
is always at a distance.

13:06.897 --> 13:10.855
I'm better from afar.

13:10.939 --> 13:13.313
I'm all scars up close.

13:13.397 --> 13:16.480
♪♪♪

13:16.563 --> 13:18.438
You know of kintsugi?

13:18.522 --> 13:19.814
Hm?

13:19.897 --> 13:21.814
It is the practice
of making art

13:21.897 --> 13:23.188
by breaking something special

13:23.271 --> 13:26.188
and gluing it back together
with gold.

13:26.271 --> 13:28.105
Your scars

13:28.188 --> 13:30.480
do not mean you are broken.

13:30.563 --> 13:32.105
They are proof you are healed.

13:32.188 --> 13:35.146
Breaking is healing.

13:35.230 --> 13:37.480
Kintsugi.

13:37.563 --> 13:41.522
Kintsugi.

13:53.146 --> 13:54.689
I don't want you to think
that I chose somebody

13:54.772 --> 13:56.230
who wouldn't be alive
very long

13:56.313 --> 13:59.980
because I thought we
were gonna get back together.

14:00.063 --> 14:02.063
I didn't think that.

14:02.146 --> 14:03.397
Usually, when your husband

14:03.480 --> 14:04.730
starts dating a younger woman,

14:04.814 --> 14:08.397
it reminds you
of your  mortality.

14:08.480 --> 14:10.021
Not this time.

14:12.939 --> 14:15.980
I'm sorry if my actions
hurt you in any way.

14:17.855 --> 14:18.897
Hey, I found
my next relationship

14:18.980 --> 14:20.647
in a hospital hallway.

14:20.730 --> 14:22.522
Maybe I led by example.

14:22.605 --> 14:24.438
When I first saw Peter,

14:24.522 --> 14:26.563
it was like watching
the "Challenger" explode,

14:26.647 --> 14:29.230
but you knew what you needed,

14:29.313 --> 14:31.980
and he put so much color
back in your cheeks.

14:32.063 --> 14:34.397
Thank him for me.

14:34.480 --> 14:38.063
Jeff, you know, nine times
out of ten, when someone

14:38.146 --> 14:39.355
walks through that doorway,
they've just gotten

14:39.438 --> 14:41.271
the worst news
that they will ever get

14:41.355 --> 14:46.146
in their life.

14:46.230 --> 14:49.689
So it would be best for her

14:49.772 --> 14:52.188
if you could find a way
to convey that

14:52.271 --> 14:54.522
her struggle

14:54.605 --> 14:56.730
is your struggle.

14:59.522 --> 15:01.855
We still have to deal
with Thursday.

15:04.063 --> 15:06.730
I'd like you to come over
to Dee Dee's,

15:06.814 --> 15:09.355
bring Peter.

15:09.438 --> 15:10.814
You open to that?

15:10.897 --> 15:13.105
- Yeah.
- Mm.

15:13.188 --> 15:15.563
That was easier
than I thought it would be.

15:15.647 --> 15:17.689
[both laugh]

15:24.230 --> 15:27.105
Whatever you need,
I'm here for you.

15:29.647 --> 15:32.730
The... second line
of treatment pushed

15:32.814 --> 15:34.355
my white blood cell count

15:34.438 --> 15:37.689
past the point of remission.

15:40.188 --> 15:42.271
I'm in remission.

15:42.355 --> 15:45.480
[laughs]

15:45.563 --> 15:47.397
I love you so much.

15:47.480 --> 15:48.855
[both laugh]

15:48.939 --> 15:50.230
Oh, my God.

15:50.313 --> 15:52.897
I have so many credit cards
to pay off.

15:57.772 --> 15:59.146
[hums]

16:01.146 --> 16:02.772
I am so, so happy

16:02.855 --> 16:04.814
to hear the good news
about your health.

16:04.897 --> 16:08.188
Thank you.
I'm... Vivian, by the way.

16:08.271 --> 16:09.772
I'm Seb.

16:09.855 --> 16:12.146
[convivial indistinct chatter]

16:12.230 --> 16:13.855
♪ "How Would They Know"
by Margaret Lewis playing ♪

16:13.939 --> 16:16.397
♪ You say ♪

16:16.480 --> 16:19.939
♪ Scarlet's my name ♪

16:20.021 --> 16:21.188
Arigatou.

16:21.271 --> 16:22.563
Put that back.
No, no,

16:22.647 --> 16:24.105
we don't do that.

16:24.188 --> 16:27.397
♪♪♪

16:27.480 --> 16:28.647
[Peter] Oh, man!

